# Importing useful libraries 
using PyPlot 
using FFTW 

# Create array for t + related variables
t=0.000001;
t=0:t:0.04;
N = length(t)
f = 1/(N*t)  # spacing in frequency domain


# Create waves/signals  + related variables
fc=20000;
fm=1000;
f=cos.(2*fm.*t)
c=cos.(2*fc.*t)
=f.*c


# Fourier Transforms of each wave
F = fft(f);
C=fft(c);
=fft();

#create array of freq values stored in f_axis. First element maps to 0Hz (for fft)
f_axis = (0:N-1)*f;    
#Label the frequency axis in Hz
N = length(t);
f = 1/(N*t)  # spacing in frequency domain

#create array of freq values stored in f_axis. (for fftshift) 
if mod(N,2)==0    # case N even
    f_axisSh = (-N/2:N/2-1)*f;    
else   # case N odd
    f_axisSh = (-(N-1)/2 : (N-1)/2)*f; 
end


# Plotting of modulating wave
figure(); plot(t,f);
PyPlot.title("f(t) [Modulating wave]"); 
plt.axis([0, 0.003, -1, 1]); 

# Plotting of modulating wave's fft
figure(figsize=(6.4,2.5)); plot(f_axis, abs.(F),".-");
xlabel("Frequency in Hz");
PyPlot.title("FFT of Modulating wave ");

# Plotting of modulating wave's fft after fftshift
figure(figsize=(6.4,4.5));
PyPlot.margins(x=-0.4,y=0.1); 
plot(f_axisSh, fftshift(abs.(F)),".-"); 
xlabel("Frequency in Hz");
plt.axis([-2000, 2000, 0, 500]);
PyPlot.title("F() [FFT of Modulating wave - shifted] ");

It can be a bit difficult to tell but the sidebands are 1000 Hz away from the carrier frequency. The reason it is hard to tell is because the FFT is imperfect and so is the scaling of this plot. The plot has been scaled this way to show a clear distinction between the sidebands and the carrier frequency.

Answers to questions¶

  • If the frequency of the modulating frequency is doubled, then the sidebands move away from the carrier frequency (from 1000 Hz away to 2000 Hz away)

  • If the ampltitude of the modulating frequency is doubled, then the magnitude of the sidebands is also doubled

f=square_wave(t);
c=cos.(2*fc.*t)
=f.*c
=f.*c


# Fourier Transforms of each wave

C=fft(c);
=fft();

f = 1/(N*t)  # spacing in frequency domain

#create array of freq values stored in f_axis. (for fftshift) 
if mod(N,2)==0    # case N even
    f_axisSh = (-N/2:N/2-1)*f;    
else   # case N odd
    f_axisSh = (-(N-1)/2 : (N-1)/2)*f; 
end

# Plotting of modulating wave
figure(); plot(t,f);
PyPlot.title("f(t) [Modulating wave]");

PyPlot.title("F() [FFT of Modulating wave - shifted] ");

Answers:¶

  • Nyquist rate would be (2 x 41k) = 82 kHz -> period of 0.00000121s My initial sampling rate is just about good enough at 0.000001s. Perhaps a higher sampling rate is called for. (I changed it to 0.0000001 and it has yielded a cleaner result)

output_of_rectifier = abs.();
output_of_rectifierF=fft(output_of_rectifier)
#BPF prep
CutoffL=20; #lower cutoff frequency
CutoffH=5000; #upper cutoff frequency

NL= ceil(Int,(CutoffL/(8*pi*N))*N) #find cuttoff indexes for array with N values
NH= floor(Int,(CutoffH/(8*pi*N))*N) #find cuttoff indexes for array with N values

#Demodulation step 2: applying LPF to ()  C()
bpfOR=output_of_rectifierF;
bpfOR[1:NL].=0; bpfOR[NH:N-NH].=0; bpfOR[N-NL:N].=0;

output_of_filter = real( ifft( bpfOR ));

# Plotting of the rectifier's output
figure();plot(t,output_of_rectifier);PyPlot.title("Output of rectifier");plt.axis([0, 0.003, 0, 2]);

# Create waves/signals  + related variables

x1=cos.(2*fm1.*t)
x2=cos.(2*fm2.*t)
c=cos.(2*fc.*t)
s=sin.(2*fc.*t)
1=x1.*c
2=x2.*s
=1+2




# Fourier Transforms of each relevant wave
=fft();

#create array of freq values stored in f_axis. First element maps to 0Hz (for fft)
f_axis = (0:N-1)*f;    
#Label the frequency axis in Hz
N = length(t);
f = 1/(N*t)  # spacing in frequency domain

#create array of freq values stored in f_axis. (for fftshift) 
if mod(N,2)==0    # case N even
    f_axisSh = (-N/2:N/2-1)*f;    
else   # case N odd
    f_axisSh = (-(N-1)/2 : (N-1)/2)*f; 
end


# Plotting of modulating waves + s
figure(figsize=(13,4.5)); plot(t,x1); PyPlot.title("x1(t)"); plt.axis([0, 0.0054, -1.5, 1.5]);
figure(figsize=(13,4.5)); plot(t,x2); PyPlot.title("x2(t)"); plt.axis([0, 0.0054, -1.5, 1.5]);
figure(figsize=(13,4.5)); plot(t,1); PyPlot.title("1(t)"); plt.axis([0, 0.0054, -1.5, 1.5]);
figure(figsize=(13,4.5)); plot(t,2); PyPlot.title("2(t)"); plt.axis([0, 0.0054, -1.5, 1.5]);
figure(figsize=(13,4.5)); plot(t,); PyPlot.title("(t)"); plt.axis([0, 0.0054, -1.5, 1.5]);






#Demodulation step 1: multipliying  with carrier
c=.*c
C=fft(c);
s=.*s
S=fft(s);


#LPF prep
Cutoff1=500; #cutoff frequency
N1= ceil(Int,(Cutoff1/(8*pi*N))*N) #find cuttoff indexes for array with N values
Cutoff2=1500; #cutoff frequency
N2= floor(Int,(Cutoff2/(8*pi*N))*N) #find cuttoff indexes for array with N values

#Demodulation step 2: applying LPF to ()  C()
lpfC=C
lpfC[N1:N-N1].=0;
lpfS=S
lpfS[N2:N-N2].=0;




#Demodulation step 3: apply inverse fft to LPF[ ()  C() ] to get 0.5f(t) signal
fd1 = real(ifft(lpfC))
fd2 = real(ifft(lpfS))


# Plotting of reconstructed modulating waves after lpf
figure(figsize=(13,4.5)); plot(t,real(c)); PyPlot.title("y1(t) before LPF");  plt.axis([0, 0.0054, -1.5, 1.5]); 

figure(figsize=(13,4.5)); plot(t,real(s)); PyPlot.title("y2(t) before LPF"); plt.axis([0, 0.0054, -1.5, 1.5]); 


# Plotting of reconstructed modulating waves after lpf
figure(figsize=(13,4.5)); plot(t,real(fd1)); PyPlot.title("e1(t)");  plt.axis([0, 0.0054, -1.5, 1.5]); 

figure(figsize=(13,4.5)); plot(t,real(fd2)); PyPlot.title("e2(t)"); plt.axis([0, 0.0054, -1.5, 1.5]); 


# Plotting of signal (t) wave's fft after fftshift
figure(figsize=(13,4.5)); PyPlot.margins(x=-0.4,y=0.1); plot(f_axisSh, fftshift(abs.()),"-"); xlabel("Frequency in Hz");
plt.axis([-22000, 22000, 0, 12500]);PyPlot.title("() ");

6.3 (1)¶

The Nyquist rate for this system would be two times the carrrier frequency or 10kHz x 2 = 20 kHz.

6.3 (2)¶

The transmitted waveform would have a bandwidth of B2.

6.3 (3)¶

The higher the phase difference (up to 90 degrees) the greater amount of crosstalk between the 'channels' (for the lack of a better term that I can think of).
